{"runId":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro@2026-05-13T15-07-47-317Z","slug":"the-jsonb-seduction","locale":"fr","model":"openai/gpt-oss-120b:nitro","modelPath":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro","createdAt":"2026-05-13T15:07:52.302Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2025-12-29--the-jsonb-seduction/index.mdx","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2025-12-29--the-jsonb-seduction/fr/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/the-jsonb-seduction/fr/openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro/2026-05-13T15-07-47-317Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"5f06fc45c6cafa097a503ef6364c5de73ba38e7ac53442da9a6385355155df99","outputHash":"703d8c8bf99a50d89d28798245c8f531b7794ebea2b0013f325e98e2c748d3f2","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"The article argues that JSONB in PostgreSQL is a useful tool for storing semi‑structured data—such as webhook payloads, logs, user settings, or LLM configuration objects—but it becomes a source of technical debt when teams use it as a shortcut for undefined schemas and then treat the blob as primary business data. It illustrates a common pattern: a JSONB column is added to avoid early schema decisions, later proliferates into many inconsistent versions, forces scattered validation logic into application code, and incurs costly full‑table scans or complex indexes. The piece distinguishes legitimate use cases (immutable or rarely‑queried documents fetched by a stable key) from misuse (frequent relational queries on nested fields), and recommends a hybrid approach that keeps core relational columns while isolating truly flexible data in JSONB. The tone is a mix of analytical rant and practical tutorial, using the metaphor of “deferring schema decisions” as the database equivalent of “I’ll clean my room later.”","totalInputTokens":10758,"totalOutputTokens":3032,"totalCacheReadTokens":6144,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":3812,"totalCostUsd":0.000965322,"pricingSource":"local-openrouter-estimate","telemetry":{"model":"openai/