{"runId":"qwen-qwen3-32b-nitro@2026-05-13T15-08-04-918Z","slug":"the-jsonb-seduction","locale":"fr","model":"qwen/qwen3-32b:nitro","modelPath":"qwen-qwen3-32b-nitro","createdAt":"2026-05-13T15:08:29.848Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2025-12-29--the-jsonb-seduction/index.mdx","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2025-12-29--the-jsonb-seduction/fr/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/the-jsonb-seduction/fr/qwen-qwen3-32b-nitro/2026-05-13T15-08-04-918Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"5f06fc45c6cafa097a503ef6364c5de73ba38e7ac53442da9a6385355155df99","outputHash":"4c47e6b6e6a719bde18eb2edfd49a192c330a46011f4c40d0cb2a9161e5e1ae4","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"**Summary:**  \nThe article argues that PostgreSQL's JSONB type is often misused as a shortcut to avoid defining schemas, leading to technical debt and inconsistent data models. While JSONB is appropriate for semi-structured data like webhook payloads, event logs, or LLM configurations, its misuse as a catch-all \"schema-on-read\" solution creates hidden complexity, fragmented validation, and performance issues (e.g., full-table scans). The author critiques the pattern of deferring schema decisions to application code, framing JSONB as a \"temporary solution\" that becomes permanent without intentional design. The intended audience is developers and architects, with a tone blending technical analysis and cautionary critique. Key metaphors include JSONB as a \"database equivalent of 'I'll clean my room later'\" and a \"schema drift\" problem where validation shifts from the database to scattered application logic.","totalInputTokens":10045,"totalOutputTokens":8477,"totalCacheReadTokens":2048,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":20196,"totalCostUsd":0.00283808,"pricingSource":"local-openrouter-estimate","telemetry":{"model":"qwen/qwen3-32b:nitro","chunkSize":"6p","totalChunks":10,"totalInputTokens":10045,"totalOutputTokens":8477,"totalCacheReadTo